  "opinion": "As a woman in my late 40s who’s worked part-time in sales while raising two children, I’ve seen how the gender gap in science isn’t just about numbers—it’s about the invisible barriers that make it feel impossible for many of us to even try. My parents had very different educational backgrounds: my mom only went to lower secondary school, while my dad has a bachelor’s degree, which shaped my early understanding of what ‘science’ meant. I grew up reading novels and cooking, not equations, so when I first learned about STEM fields, I felt like I was missing a piece of the puzzle. Today, I see this gap as deeply personal—it’s not just about women being underrepresented in labs or universities, but about the lack of role models who look like us in everyday life. I’m depressed a lot, and that makes me question my own potential, especially when I see how few women are in leadership roles in science. We should address this gap by creating more inclusive spaces where girls and women feel seen and supported from a young age, not just as ‘math people’ but as thinkers who can contribute in all areas of science. It’s not about fixing something broken but about making sure everyone has a chance to thrive. How? By integrating storytelling and hands-on projects into science education, so kids don’t feel like they need to be perfect to participate. I’ve tried yoga and hiking to manage my depression, but I wonder if science could be more accessible too—maybe through community programs that connect people with real-world problems they care about.",
